Very interesting.  Thanks, John, for the history lesson.

I was thinking of Henry the VIII&#39;s reign and the lack of standardization 
at that time.  You are suggesting that the standards had firmed up 
considerably in the latter part of the 16th century.  Was the chaos of 
private spelling, as you refer to it, difficult to comprehend, or did it 
just slow reading down because one was forced to decipher unusually 
spelled words too frequently?

It makes sense that professional scribes would tend toward 
standardization.  Since they spent their working lives writing, they 
would be likely to develop spellings that were consistent over time.  Of 
course, I would suspect that a large part of the spelling 
inconsistencies prior to this had to do with the poor fit between the 
Roman alphabet and English phonemes.  It would not be possible to spell 
words in so many different ways if the alphabet fit English better as QS 
does. 

The bare statement that the official Dutch orthography changes every few 
decades implies that some organization with authority makes that 
change.  What is that organization?  The Dutch government?  A language 
academy?  It appears to me that standardized does mean &quot;fixed&quot; in 
English because there is no authority to force a change on a language 
spoken around the world.

I am not advocating anarchy in spelling -- just some freedom for 
individuality.  I believe that the percentage of words which people 
would spell differently would be relatively limited and would not 
greatly impede readability.

Paige

P.S.  Moira, thanks for your input.

John Cowan wrote:
&gt;
&gt; pgabhart scripsit:
&gt; &gt; When Shakespeare was penning his plays, I believe standardized spelling
&gt; &gt; was a concept that did not exist.
&gt;
&gt; It most definitely did. The First Folio&#39;s spelling is nowhere near
&gt; as standardized as any modern work, but it is far from the chaos of
&gt; private spelling in the early 17th century. Scribes and scriveners
&gt; (professional letter-writers for the illiterate) had been converging on
&gt; a standard spelling of late Middle and early Modern English since 1422,
&gt; when the Brewers Company (a guild) first started to issue their records
&gt; in English. Before the Norman Conquest, there had been a similarly
&gt; standardized spelling of Old English, some of which persisted into
&gt; early Middle English times. When Tolkien was not writing about elves
&gt; and hobbits, one of the things he did was to discover that the various
&gt; manuscripts of an early 13th-century work called the _Ancrene Wisse_,
&gt; though in different handwritings, had extremely consistent spellings
&gt; and dialect markers, showing that the various scribes had learned how
&gt; to spell English in a school of some sort, a good two centuries after
&gt; the Norman Conquest had supposedly sent English underground.
&gt;
&gt; &gt; Nevertheless, the fact that publishers &quot;want&quot; a standardized spelling
&gt; &gt; has more to do with tradition than necessity I expect.
&gt;
&gt; Of the written languages of the world (most are unwritten), many lack a
&gt; standard orthography: Cherokee is an example. But as far as is known,
&gt; every language where literacy is widespread and there is no competing
&gt; written language commonly used (Cherokee records, after all, are mostly
&gt; in English) has converged on a common standard or a few standards.
&gt; And no language has ever reverted in its public written works to
&gt; unstandardized spelling.
&gt;
&gt; &gt; Once a spelling is &quot;fixed,&quot; no one has the authority to change it in 
&gt; the
&gt; &gt; future.
&gt;
&gt; Standardized doesn&#39;t mean fixed. The official Dutch orthography changes
&gt; every few decades.
&gt;
&gt; &gt; Another issue is involves the changes the publishing industry will
&gt; &gt; undergo in the future. Before long, it may be that books will be
&gt; &gt; printed as the demand calls for them, and the concept of a first
&gt; &gt; printing of a certain number of copies may disappear from the industry
&gt; &gt; altogether.
&gt;
&gt; Print-on-demand doesn&#39;t affect the fundamental division between edited
&gt; and unedited works. It&#39;s true that there is much more unedited publicly
&gt; available work than ever before.
&gt;
&gt; And multiple standards with automatic conversion will *depend* on the
&gt; existence of an internationalized base version, because no individual
&gt; accent continues to make all the distinctions that, collectively, all
&gt; accents make.
&gt;
